 religions. "Mysticism" can refer to either direct experience of God or the claim that such experience is ineffable, and both senses of the term are carefully analyzed in the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMysticism. 0aProcess philosophy. 0aProcess theology. 4aPhilosophy : Metaphysics. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aPhilosophy : Process Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Mysticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theology. 7aRELIGION / Mysticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849136340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438491363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438491363/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles